[SourceTitle "01 Open Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/655711"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 dxe4 7. d5 Ne5 8. fxe4 e6 
9. Nf3 {A solid move that equalizes with exact play by both players.} Bd6 {The 
strategy for white in this game is that of simplification. The potential of a passed 
pawn at d5 leads to favorable endgames.} 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Bf4 {Nd3+ is 
also interesting. White will maintain the strong pawn at d5 and seek refuge with 
0-0.} Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Bxf4 14. Qxf4 O-O {If instead exd4 then white should 0-0 with 
good play (or a transposition).} 15. O-O exd5 16. Rad1 $1 {Black stil has some 
problems to solve in this heavy piece endgame.} *

[Event "Crush the Slav with the Boor Attack"]
[Site "Open Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8...a6 Positional"]
[Black "Queen Sacrifice."]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 Open Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/655715"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 dxe4 7. d5 Ne5 8. fxe4 {A 
smart move cutting out any pesky checks on b5.} a6 {By no means the only move (Qd4 
and Bf4 are playable here), but I would like to share with you an interesting 
sacrifice that still remains unplayed in practice.} 9. Nf3 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 e6 11. Bg5 
Be7 12. O-O-O exd5 {White now delves into complications, hunting the king.} 13. e5 $5 
Bg4 14. exf6 {A Cool exchange of a queen for three minor pieces that will leave your 
opponent gasping for air.} Bxf3 15. fxe7 Qd6 16. gxf3 {With 3 pieces for the queen 
black should take care. As Dirty Harry once said, 'You feeling lucky ?'} Rc8 17. Bd3 
$1 {Encouraging black to play d4 when Kb1 is a cute meta block.} f6 18. Be3 Qxe7 19. 
Kb1 $13 {White is now ready to recapture d5 with a position that Tal would have loved 
to play.} *

