1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 dxe4 7. d5 Ne5 8. fxe4 g6 
$6 {Black ignores the center at his peril.} 9. Nf3 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Bg7 11. e5 {The 
dynamic pawn duo steamrolls black.} Ng4 12. Bb5+ {If Bd7 block then Qxg4 collects a 
knight.} Kf8 13. e6 $16 {Cutting to the heart of the position. Black is under heavy 
attack. If Bd7 block then Qxg4 collects a knight.} *

[Event "Crush the Slav with the Boor Attack"]
[Site "Open Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7...Nb8"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 Open Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/655721"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 dxe4 7. d5 Nb8 {An 
interesting move. Black realizes that the knight is more of a liability on e5 and 
instead seeks to block the center with a pawn. For the white side there is still the 
d5 pawn which often becomes a passed pawn. This variation calls for the strategy of 
simplification by white and careful play on the dark squares (where white has 
weakness).} 8. fxe4 e5 9. Nf3 Bc5 {The sharpest move. If white plays Nxe5 then black 
will castle followed by Re8 with dangerous play.} 10. Bd3 {White would like to play 
Qe2 followed by Be3 and play for a longterm strategy of exchanging pieces to increase 
the potential of the d5 pawn. There is also attacking chances on the black king due 
to the open F file.} O-O {Ng4 would be met with Qe2 followed by Rf1 when black 
becomes overextended.} 11. Qe2 Bg4 12. Be3 Nbd7 13. O-O Qb6 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. Kh1 $10 
{Both sides have their trumps and the position is balanced.} *

