[Event "Crush the Slav with the Boor Attack"]
[Site "Closed Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Variation"]
[Black "with pawn to f6."]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Closed Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/655724"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 e6 7. e5 Nd7 8. f4 Be7 9. 
Nf3 {The position has the appearance of the Classical Steinitz French but with one 
key difference: the lack of c-pawns on favors white as there is cement like 
protection of the d4 square.} O-O 10. Be2 {A personal preference of mine. Bd3 is 
fully playable and perhaps even the strongest move but I like to keep control of the 
d4 square fully and finish development with no stress about Nb4. The position has a 
slow character and it is no shame moving the bishop from e2 to d3 in the future.} Qb6 
11. O-O f6 {This is really the only way black can pressure the center.} 12. Kh1 
{Almost always a useful move in such positions. As we shall see it can even be used 
for attacking purposes with Rg1.} fxe5 13. fxe5 $14 {[%cal 
Ba2a3,Bb2b4,Bc3a4,Be2d3,Bf3g5,Bd1e1,Be1g3,Bg3h3][%csl 
Bb4,Ba4,Bd3,Bg5,Be1,Bg3,Bh3,Bc8]} Rxf3 {This thematic exchange sacrifice is not quite 
correct here, but what else is there for black ? White has more than one way to 
improve the position: a3-b4-Na4 to cramp the queenside; Qd3-Ng5 to harry the king; 
more of the same with Bd3-Na4-Qe1-Qg3-Qh3. All three plans are valid for 
white--besides the rook sacrifice black is just sitting !} 14. Bxf3 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 
Nxd4 16. Nxd5 $1 {A spectacular denouncement of black's play.} exd5 17. Bxd5+ Kh8 18. 
Rf7 {The black pieces are a disorganized mess with problems on the 7th and 8th 
ranks.} Bb4 19. Bxb7 {Black does not get a moment's rest.} Nxe5 20. Bxa8 Nxf7 21. Be3 
{The a7 pawn is dropping and white has a winning endgame.} *

[Event "Crush the Slav with the Boor Attack"]
[Site "Closed Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
