[Black "with pawn at f5."]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Closed Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/655776"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 e6 7. e5 Nd7 8. f4 Be7 9. 
Nf3 O-O 10. Be2 f5 11. O-O a6 {a6-b5 take a long time to amount to meaningful 
counterplay on the queenside, just the same Qb6 also fails to crack the d4 and b2 
strongholds.} 12. Kh1 {Our favorite move in this structure.} b5 13. Rg1 Nb6 {It is 
also possible to prepare this first with h3 and capture with the pawn at g4. White 
has pressure either way.} 14. g4 fxg4 15. Rxg4 Bd7 16. Qg1 {A useful attack to cross 
black's plan of bringing his light square bishop to the kingside.} Rf7 17. Bd3 {The 
stage is set for a siege of the black kingside.} *

[Event "Crush the Slav with the Boor Attack"]
[Site "Closed Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
