[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Closed Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/656224"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Nc6 6. e4 e6 7. e5 Ng8 8. Be3 Qb6 {A 
natural move that delays the kingside formation.} 9. Qd2 Bd7 10. Rd1 {A move that 
would make Nimzowitch smile. White over protects d4 and does not show his hand on the 
kingside.} Na5 11. Bd3 Rc8 {Black is playing a common attack formation for French 
queenside play.} 12. Nge2 {An interesting position where white is building up for 
long term king-side pressure.} Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. O-O {Fully developed and with a 
secure center white is finally ready to make progress on the kingside. It is 
important to not play pawn to f4 unless it is absolutely correct as we will have a 
bad bishop and close off our pieces.} Bb4 15. Nf4 {[%csl Bh5,Bd3] This knight 
placement creates some good attacking chances. If black plays g6 then we can play Nd3 
and leave him with permanent holes on the dark squares.} Ne7 {[%csl Rh5,Bd3]} 16. Nh5 
Nf5 17. g4 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Kf8 19. f4 *

