[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "crush-the-slav-with-the-boor-attack/course/11611, variation/658381"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Bf5 6. Bg5 a6 {This move shows that 
black understands the basic traps of the variation and is suggested by IM Bartell in 
his Chessable Slav course.} 7. Rc1 {White is waiting for black to play Nc6 when pawn 
to e4 would still work as in the main trap line.} Nbd7 8. e3 {In these lines so far 
we have looked at playing the most aggressive e4 break, but pawn to e3 is quite good 
and normal. The pawn may even advance at the right moment.} h6 9. Bh4 {In general 
white should avoid trading bishop for knight unless it leads to a concrete material 
advantage.} Qb6 {An adventurous move that will allow me to show some thematic play 
for white.} 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Qxb2 12. Nge2 {White has no problem sacrificing a 
pawn for development.} b5 13. e4 {The position calls for rapid attack through the 
center.} b4 $2 14. Na4 Qxa2 15. Qxa6 {[%cal Bc1c8][%csl Bc8] Even if black avoids 
immediate mate we will have a strong gambit attacking position.} *

