1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 Qb6 {Black avoids playing Nc6 to 
sidestep the d5 pawn push tempo. I will give two options vs. the Qb6 variation.} 6. 
e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 {It is important for white not to capture the pawn as black has a 
strong answer in Ng4 followed by blockading the e4 isolated pawn.} 8. Bb5+ $5 {If 
black blocks with Bd7 the we have fxe5 (as now Ng4 is impossible) followed by a 
timely Nd5 when the complications favor white.} Nc6 $1 {the best to maintain the 
tension and access to the g4 square in the event of fxe5.} 9. d5 Bb4 $1 {Again black 
maintains the tension by attacking the b5 bishop.} 10. Qd3 a6 11. Ba4 Qa5 $1 {yet 
another computer like tension maintaining move (do you think your average opponent 
will know this line ? perhaps, perhaps...)} 12. Bd1 $1 {White does well not to 
exchange on c6 and the game is complex.} Nd4 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bc5 
{We have already seen this pawn structure and plan from the Open variation with Nb8. 
White has weathered the storm and now has a passed pawn albeit a bad bishop on f3. 
The game is balanced.} 16. Be3 Qb6 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. Qe2 Bd7 19. Qf2 *

