1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 g6 6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 Bg7 8. Nf3 {My 
idea here is that white should complete development before launching an attack with 
e5. Bc4 and Bb5+ have been played here with success. More research is needed in this 
hybrid Grunfeld type middlegame.} O-O 9. Be2 b6 {We are following the game Boor - 
Colas Philadelphia 2013.} 10. O-O Bb7 11. Qd3 {This is my improvement over breaking 
the tension with pawn to e5. In the game I was put off by Ba6 but in hindsight I 
realize that black would only be weakening his position by trading light square 
bishops.} Nc6 12. Bf4 $14 {The stage is set for an interesting battle. White 
maintains the classical center while black has arranged the double fianchetto. White 
will play Rad1 solidifying the center and looking to press black by keeping the 
tension. Depending on how black responds we can break with e5 or d5 or just simply 
improve our position with moves like Kh1, h3, a3 and eventually organize an attack on 
the king with Qd3-d2-Bh6. Black has to always be careful about white playing e5 and 
Ng5 and Qh3 as well; 'from a strong center springs a strong attack'.} *

