1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 e6 6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 Bb4 8. Bg5 Qa5 
9. Bxf6 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Kf2 Qb2+ 12. Be2 gxf6 13. Nf3 {We continue with the 
critical gambit line. With the idea of Ba6. I feel that most opponent's would play 
for this idea.} b6 14. Rb1 {Perhaps this should be known as the poisoned pawn 
variation.} Qxa2 {If 14...Qa3 then white can complete development with 15. Qd2 and 
have full compensation for the pawn.} 15. Nd2 {Planning Nc4 closing the net around 
the black queen.} Qa3 {The queen escapes but now we can demonstrate the power of our 
development and mobile pawn center.} 16. e5 {Securing an outpost at d6 for the knight 
as well as threats on the h1-a8 diagonal.} Qe7 17. Bf3 Bb7 18. Ne4 fxe5 19. Nd6+ Qxd6 
20. Bxb7 {Black will not have quite enough pawns for a full rook.} *

