1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 e6 {A challenging move. Black 
anticipates pawn to e4 by building a solid center and keep his eye on the b4 square.} 
6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 Bb4 8. Bg5 {A new development (over my prior suggestion of Qd3 
which is still quite playable) first played by the strong Serbian Grandmaster 
Ivanisevic in 2017.} h6 9. Bxf6 {If Bh4 then black would win a valuable center pawn 
with g5 followed by Ne4.} Qxf6 10. Nf3 O-O 11. Bc4 {White has a classical attacking 
formation that should would be the dream of a King's Gambiteer.} Nc6 12. O-O Rd8 13. 
e5 {White declares his intentions for central space and kingside expansion.} Qe7 14. 
Ne2 Bd7 15. a3 Ba5 16. Qd3 Be8 17. Kh1 Rac8 18. Rad1 {[%cal 
Bc4a2,Be2f4,Bd4d5,Ba2b1,Bf4h5][%csl Bh7] We have followed the path of Ivanisevic 
which he won in great attacking style. White has excellent attacking prospects with 
the plan of eventually playing d5 and launching a kingside attack. The fact that 
black has the two bishops does not have great impact due to the strong white center.} 
*

