1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 a6 6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 8. dxe5 
Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Ng4 10. Nd5 Ra7 {Playing it safe but as we shall see this can create 
disharmony in the black ranks.} 11. Ke1 Bc5 12. Nf3 {Here it is important to realize 
that 12...Nf2 would lose to 13.b4! trapping the overtended pieces, while 12...Bf2 
13.Ke2 would lead to an equally unpleasant entanglement.} Nc6 13. Bf4 Nf2 14. Rc1 
Nxe4 {If 14...Nxh1 15. Rxc5 leaves black's pieces stranded on poor squares.} 15. Rc4 
Bf5 16. Bd3 {[%cal Bd3f5,Bc4c5,Bc4e4][%csl Bf5,Be4] White is winning material.} *

