1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 a6 {A useful semi-waiting move that 
prevents tactics on the b5 square.} 6. e4 {Our programmed play of central expansion.} 
dxe4 {Of course black could defer to closed lines with 6...e6 but we have already 
covered this idea.} 7. fxe4 e5 {We should give this central counter blow careful 
consideration. In some variations (when black lags in development) we can afford to 
bypass with d5 while in other situations we should counterattack.} 8. dxe5 {Usually 
we do not capture this pawn, but in this exact position it is good to do so as black 
has weakened the queenside. This may seem like a minor detail but as will be seen 
every difference does count in chess.} Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 {White has their eyes on the d5 
square.} Ng4 10. Nd5 Nf2+ 11. Ke2 {Avoiding any future checks on b4.} Nxh1 12. Nc7+ 
Kd8 13. Nxa8 {[%cal Bg2g3,Bc1e3,Bf1g2][%csl Be3,Bb6] The knight at a8 has a much 
easier time escaping the corner. White will eventually round up the black knight at 
h1 with pawn to g3 and Bg2.} *

