1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. e4 dxe4 6. d5 Nb8 7. f3 {A new move. 
Similar to the Blackmar–Diemer Gambit, this gambit should lead to fertile grounds 
for fans of sharp and uncompromising attacking play.} exf3 8. Nxf3 Nf6 9. Bc4 g6 10. 
O-O Bg7 11. Qe1 {The queen goes to h4. This is the traditional attack scheme in the 
analogues line of the Diemer gambit but in this case the pawn at d5 hampers black's 
development.} O-O 12. Qh4 Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Bf5 {One of a few possible set-ups. Once you 
get the feel for this attack you will find that the play for white is actually quite 
free flowing and thematic.} 14. Bb3 {Covering the pawn at b2. White should show some 
restraint before going in for the attack by placing the pieces on their best 
squares.} Nbd7 15. Bh6 {The computer doth protest but white has setup a classic 
attacking formation with intentions of Ng5,Rae1, Nce4 and a siege of the black 
fortification. Indeed a whole book could be wrote about this sub variation gambit but 
I will leave it to you dear reader for further exploration and research.} *

